## Update 12/18/2023 ##

Last week we found out that toggling the wifi behavior doesn't fix this behavior, it's breaking more than it fixes. 

Behavior that the wifi is connected, but the axios library isn't able to perform a request is still there.

Is there a way we can enable more in-depth axios logging to analyze the issue?

### Describe the bug


When a device is switching between wifi / cellular 4G / wifi our app isn't able to perform a network request after returning to wifi for 10-15 minutes. 

We're already hooked up to the Networkconnectionchanged events, which returns isConnected: true and isInternetReachable: true. Even a separate MQTT client is able to reconnect after returning into the wifi. the issue is realy with the axios instance.

Our app is using a background task to perform requests every 20 sec to a given backend. when ther's poor or no wifi, the device looses it's connection and switches to 4G. Once back in the wifi, the app ( using axios to consume the api) isnt'able to get through the network stack of android of 10-15 minutes. After this period a new tcp session is initiated by the device and the requests are passing through.
After months of investigation we found out that toggling the WifiManager.forceWifiUsageWithOptions(true, noInternet: false/true) fixes the issue. After toggling this setting Axios is able to perform a network request directly. We're currently implementing this as a workaround, but a real solid solution is needed.

When specific logging is required, we're able to reproduce this 100% in a certain envinroment. so if code snippets are provided to check additional parameters, we can fix that.

