### Describe the issue

Axios provides `lookup` parameter in `CreateAxiosDefaults` to let us use custom hostname lookup logic. But there's two problems with it:
1) This only makes sense for NodeJS because it's impossible to use custom hostname lookup in browser. But even when it comes to NodeJS, Axios prefer to use `Agent["lookup"]` instead of `CreateAxiosDefaults["lookup"]`. The second one will be used only if the first one is undefined. Why do we have 2 almost identical separate interfaces for the same thing?
2) When providing custom hostname lookup in NodeJS environment the common sense and safety reasoning require us to provide both `Agent["lookup"]` and `CreateAxiosDefaults["lookup"]` by wrapping the same lookup function for different interfaces. Thanks to poor typing of `CreateAxiosDefaults["lookup"]` we need to provide a monstrous validation logic

So the proposal if to remove `CreateAxiosDefaults["lookup"]` in favor of `Agent["lookup"]` which is the current behavior

### Example Code

```typescript
import { LookupFunction } from 'node:net';
import axios, { LookupAddressEntry } from 'axios';
import { z } from 'zod';

// LookupFunction is a NodeJS standard type for proving custom hostname resolving
const dnsLookup: LookupFunction = (hostname, options, callback) => {
    // Some impl here
}
// Axios prefer to use `Agent["lookup"]` instead of `CreateAxiosDefaults["lookup"]`. The second one will be
// used only if the first one is undefined. Why do we have 2 almost identical separate interfaces for the same thing?
const httpsAgent = new Agent({ lookup: dnsLookup })
const axiosInstance = axios.create({
    httpsAgent,
    // Since CreateAxiosDefaults["lookup"] contract is close enough to NodeJS LookupFunction, we can use NodeJS LookupFunction after
    // some boring mapping to ensure its compatibility
    lookup: (hostname, options, cb) => {
        // Because axios type `options` with just `object` we need to ensure it's compatible with NodeJS LookupFunction options
        // by using this monstrous validation. Yep, this is price of safety.
        const nodeJsLookupOptions = z.object({
            family: z.union([z.number(), z.literal("IPv4"), z.literal("IPv6")]).optional(),
            hints: z.number().optional(),
            all: z.boolean().optional(),
            order: z.union([z.literal("ipv4first"), z.literal("ipv6first"), z.literal("verbatim")]).optional(),
            verbatim: z.boolean().optional()
        }).transform(it => {
            const lookupOptions: Parameters<LookupFunction>[1] = it
            return lookupOptions
        }).parse(options)
        dnsLookup(hostname, nodeJsLookupOptions, (err, address, family) => {
            const isStringAddress = typeof address === "string"
            if (isStringAddress) {
                const axiosAddressFamily = family === 4 || family === 6 ? family : undefined
                cb(err, address, axiosAddressFamily)
                return
            }

            const axiosLookupAddressEntries = address.map(it => {
                const axiosAddressFamily = it.family === 4 || it.family === 6 ? it.family : undefined
                const axiosLookupAddressEntry: LookupAddressEntry = {
                    address: it.address,
                    family: axiosAddressFamily
                }
                return axiosLookupAddressEntry
            })
            cb(err, axiosLookupAddressEntries)
        })
    },
    // ...
})

// And now we are ready to use it
axiosInstance.get("https://google.com")
```

### Expected behavior

Expected behavior is to use NodeJS Agent["lookup"] as a single way to provide custom hostname resolution logic by getting rid of [`AxiosRequestConfig["lookup"]`](https://github.com/axios/axios/blob/8092aee7240220aa7913d163187b7fba8d9e5a51/index.d.ts#L369)

As a result, you no longer need to support custom contract to ensure your code does hostname resolving in your way:
```typescript
import { LookupFunction } from 'node:net';
import axios from 'axios';

// LookupFunction is a NodeJS standard type for proving custom hostname resolving
const dnsLookup: LookupFunction = (hostname, options, callback) => {
    // Some impl here
}
const httpsAgent = new Agent({ lookup: dnsLookup })
const axiosInstance = axios.create({
    httpsAgent,
    // No need to support another lookup contract! Hell yea!
    // ...
})

// And now we are ready to use it
axiosInstance.get("https://google.com")
```

