When a server responds with `429 Too Many Requests` or `503 Service Unavailable`, it often sends a `Retry-After` header indicating when the client should retry. Axios currently has no built-in way to honour this header; users must write custom interceptors in every project, or install the third-party `axios-retry` package. This should be a first-class feature in the axios core.

```js
// Opt-in per-request
const response = await axios.get('/api/data', {
  retry: {
    retries: 3,                    // max retry attempts (default: 0 = disabled)
    retryStatusCodes: [429, 503],  // which HTTP codes to retry on
    respectRetryAfter: true,       // parse Retry-After header (default: true)
    retryDelay: 1000               // fallback delay in ms if no header present
  }
});

// Or set globally
axios.defaults.retry = {
  retries: 2,
  retryStatusCodes: [429, 503],
  respectRetryAfter: true,
  retryDelay: 500
};
```

The interceptor should:
- Support both Retry-After formats: delta-seconds ("120") and HTTP-date
  ("Wed, 21 Oct 2026 07:28:00 GMT")
- Clamp negative or zero delay values to 0ms
- Only retry the configured status codes, not all errors
- Default retries: 0 (opt-in, zero breaking changes)

`axios-retry` on npm covers this but requires extra setup per project and is not maintained by the axios core team. Native support eliminates a widely-needed third-party dependency.

